Climate impacts on crop yields will lead to an additional 20 million children being malnourished by 2050. This would be catastrophic in Africa.
Other effects of climate change include air pollution, extreme wild fires, hurricanes, destruction of island nations, extinction of plant and animal species and water scarcity. Consequently, apart from heightening conflicts, these effects lead to displacement of people.





Developing nations
While nations agree that a lot needs to be done to ensure the earth is habitable for current and future generations, there are some complications. 
Firstly, the scale of emissions is huge and the sheer magnitude of the changes required to mitigate or adapt successfully to climate change would lead to significant disruptions in the way the world works in terms of industrialisation and energy production. 
For example, we would need to do away with traditional sources of energy like fossil fuels and adopt clean energy, such as solar.  There is also the issue of who should pay for this changes, with primarily developing nations who have historically had a smaller carbon footprint, arguing that developed countries should bear the responsibility for cutting emissions.



